{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The transverse momentum of the parton emitted through this splitting in the branching is related to the branching variable q ′ 2, according to the angular ordering [15] as q ⊥ = (1z)|q ′ |.",
    "z M is a parameter introduced as z M = 1ϵ to bring z as close as possible to 1 through a numerical approach by achieving ϵ → 0.According to the angular ordering, there is a value of the parton transverse momentum emitted during the branching, denoted as q 0, which leads to two regions: a perturbative region where q ⊥ > q 0 and a non-perturbative region where q ⊥ < q 0, in which α s is frozen [3].",
    "Therefore, it is possible to introduce an intermediate z-scale, referred to as dynamic-z defined as:z dyn = 1 -q 0 /q ′ (2)By introducing z dyn, the integral in 1 can be split in two parts as follows:∆(µ 2, µ 2 0) = exp - b µ 2 µ 2 0 dq ′2 q ′2 z dyn 0 dz z P (R) ba (α s, z) × exp - b µ 2 µ 2 0 dq ′2 q ′2 z M z dyn dz z P (R) ba (α s, z) = ∆ (P) µ 2, µ 2 0, q 2 0 • ∆ (NP) µ 2, µ 2 0, q 2 0.",
    "(3)In the PB Method z M → 1 while in shower-based event generators z M = z dyn.",
    "This implies that when mimicking shower-based MC event generators, the non-perturbative part of the Sudakov form factor, ∆ (NP) µ 2, µ 2 0, q 2 0, is neglected through the integral in z.To ilustrate the effect of the excluded soft gluon contribution, we show in the right part of Figure 1 a comparison of two predictions obtained by CASCADE3 for q 0 ≃ 2 GeV: one with a pure intrinsick T value, q s ≃ 1 GeV, and another one with an optimal value q s = 2.1 GeV."
